SARS commissioner Edward Kieswetter spoke with eNCA's Sally Burdett on the tax implications of the Medium-Term Budget Policy Statement presented by Finance Minister Tito Mboweni on Wednesday. Courtesy of #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - South Africa's debt is in danger of spiralling out of control, and tax increases are inevitable. READ: Cosatu has mixed reaction to Mboweni's budget speech The government needs an additional R5-billion in tax increases in the next financial year and a total of R40-billion over the next four years. eNCA's Heidi Giokos has more. Courtesy #DStv403 #eNCA Sars commissioner Edward Kieswetter says the revenue service is looking at several areas to raise additional revenue over the next few months. READ: Opposition parties react to MTBPS "The work that we do is to ensure that we improve the levels of compliance in South Africa. We know that the levels of compliance have been on a steady decline, and we are working hard to arrest that." "The second area we are focusing on is losses due to illicit and criminal activities, and there we are working hard with our sister agencies in government, the NPA along with the SIU and the Hawks to ensure we bring those criminals to book," he said. Finance Minister Tito Mboweni has painted a bleak picture of the country's finances in his Medium-Term Budget Policy Statement on Wednesday. Watch the full interview with Sars commissioner Edward Kieswetter in the video above.